I’m a writer. Wow. I believe it now.

Need some new tunes? I made a new mixtape which you can grab via my newsletter (link in bio!)

I designed this fake album cover too because, why not. I used to be a graphic designer in a past life, designing album covers and show posters for musicians like @theheadandtheheart, @krisorlowski and even my own old band The Mopes. I used to be a musician, in my 20s it was a moody surf rock band that took inspiration from Elliott Smith, Morrissey and Weezer, a quirky sound for sure. I was a semi-pro classical singer in my teen years and simultaneously was writing folk music while keeping it to myself.
I taught myself guitar right handed (I’m left handed) at 15 by writing music, not by following a book or having a teacher to guide me. As an undiagnosed Autistic kid, it all makes sense now. Music and art are and have always been my healers, self soothing tools, and important modes of self expression when I can’t get words out otherwise. 

In college, I performed my own music quite a bit as a challenge to my naturally introverted vibe. After each performance, I’d escape as quickly to my dorm room as I could to avoid people and decompress. Performing my own music was cathartic and absolutely terrifying. Will I ever do it again? I don’t know. But the magic of being someone who connects deeply with lyricism, melody and more is that I know I create a mean mixtape.

On this mixtape, you’ll find some magical sounds from @jamiethedrake, @monicamartin, @jpblues, @fruit_bats and many more musicians who make my mind ping with joy and my emotions sway. Happy listening!

I’m remembering that though social media platforms and al90rythms are kind of a nightmare at this point in virtual culture, I can still use this space for my own joy. I have memory loss and short term memory issues due to symptoms of Autism. Autism comes in many flavors with a variety of comorbidities. No one Autistic person is the same as another, our challenges vary, our coping skills are different, and it helps me to think of our diverse community as a delicious bowl full of tons of different ice cream flavors. We’re all different, all have things that make us melt and feel like our worst along with things that heighten our flavor and make us shine with joy. Seeing evidence of my efforts to bring joy into my life through photos and videos is a helper in keeping alive the memories I can’t contain in my mind. 

In 2023, I want to do a better job of documenting my life for my own joy. I want to remember. 🧡

Ok so solidifying a name for my new interview series is proving to be a challenge.

What is it:
An interview series where I dive deep into the minds of creative and fascinating people through list making. Guests will be filling out a list from one of my journals, I’ll be filling out the same list, and you’ll be prompted to do the same too so we can all use our unique perspectives to gain greater wisdom on being.

Where will it exist:
It will exist in video form in my newsletter which goes out weekly and on YouTube. I’ll post snippets of the video interview on my @52lists Insta account as well as Pinterest and TikTok. And I’m hoping I can also use the audio to share it in podcast form on all streaming platforms.
(If anyone has advice on how to extract just the audio from recorded zoom meetings, let me know!)

The Why:
My life as an author is very solitary and I profoundly miss the community I once had in the pre-pandemic world. I want to rebuild a routine of connecting with inspiring folks via the medium I love, list making. And sharing those meaningful connections with you will be sure to inspire and encourage so many! This project is something that I want to do to support your mental health and mine. I want to build community and share stories that will bring us together and lift our spirits. Through this series, I hope each of us feels less alone 🧡

It was such a joy to start this series off with the one and only Alison, a woman I’ve known for almost 10 years thanks to the wild world of the internet, blogging and female entrepreneurship.

My journal prompt of the day:
List number 2 from The 52 Lists Project: List Your Favorite Characters from books, movies etc.

When I filled out this list for the first time after publishing this guided journal in 2015, it was the first time I ever saw my gender dysphoria outside of myself and acknowledged it. Growing up, I always felt uncomfortable being identified as a girl, not so much because of what I defined as “girl” but because of what society said I could not be or experience because of being a “girl.” I always identified with male characters in books and movies. Even to this day, I feel most aligned with identities found in preteen boys on epic journeys of self discovery and mystery. Mathilda was one of the few books I read growing up that felt like it spoke to my life experience being a shy and isolated girl with a magical mind. It makes so much more sense now having been diagnosed with Autism in 2020 at the age of 34. 

Personal narratives are a wild thing. Society crafts stories about who we must be based on how we look, what body parts we have, where we grew up, and so much more. In my past, I accepted so many expectations that left me feeling so depressed, anxious and questioning. And now, it’s a gift to rest in the space of the “Hanged One,” in a state of observation, seeing all that is and was from a different angle. No action needed yet, just a clearer view so that in this stillness, I can rest and heal. Does this resonate with you?

To pause and reflect is a gift. You are more than what society dictates as true. Your personal narrative is yours to craft. Be in it, keep seeking your truth.

Episode 4 of my podcast ‘52 Lists with Moorea Seal’ is live! It was such an honor to get to interview @morganharpernichols. 

Morgan is not only mega talented but truly a kind person at heart. She is the author of the upcoming poetry and art book ‘You Are Only Just Beginning’ as well as 2 previous books in the trilogy. She’s the founder and artist behind the @thestorytellerco. You can find her on her podcast ‘The Morgan Harper Nichols Show’ as well as teaching on Skillshare. She blogs and writes an daily newsletter and somehow also is a parent to 3 year old and married to her college boyfriend. And there’s so much more. Beyond all these incredible accomplishments is a person who I admire so deeply and connect to on a level that I cannot with most.

Morgan and I are both autistic and live with ADHD. We both went through the pressures of being the eldest daughter of fathers who were pastors and leaders in their communities. We both found refuge in art and music, I writing an album when I was 19 and Morgan going on to sign a record deal in her early twenties. We both are artists and best selling authors. We both find somatic healing through riding roller coasters!!! We both find ourselves speaking in ways where others think we are speaking in metaphor and we have to correct them, what we are saying is literal, we just have a poetic way of putting things.

The parallels I feel with @morganharpernichols are profound. And honestly, I feel shocked and beyond humbled that she reached out to me after reading about my story of coming to an Autism diagnosis which I shared in @drdevonprice’s book ‘Unmasking Autism.’

Head to Spotify, Apple Podcasts, or the link in my bio to listen to the latest episode of ‘52 Lists with Moorea Seal.’ Morgan, what an honor to get to chat with you about your creative life and career, your growing up, your growth and advocacy of self and others, and so much more.

This is an episode you don’t want to miss. Get ready to feel inspired, empowered and your heart warmed. Thank you so much Morgan 💛

Now is not the past, but sometimes, it reminds me of it.

I live with pretty severe memory loss. I live with C-PTSD, and as a way to manage traumatic memories, my brain sometimes scrubs it or shoves it so far down that I can do nothing to retrieve it. 

Sometimes I feel like people think my diagnosis of Autism is an excuse for “bad” habits or “bad” behavior. I’m forgetful and easily confused in ways that impact others, especially those closest to me. So at many points in my life, I’ve thought the only responses I can choose are total submission to someone else’s will while also self shaming, or completely removing myself from the relationship entirely, sometimes dreaming of removing myself from existence. It’s been many many years since I’ve let myself go that far in my mind in seeking my own safety. And I wish relief to anyone who struggles with being alive. It’s a lot of us.

The diagnosis of Autism at age 33 seriously helped me to understand my challenges, and though others may not be able to understand unless they too deal with similar struggles and disabilities, I at least know, my intentions are good, and I have permission to fail, mess up, make mistakes and not live up to others expectations, or even my own. I’d like to, but I don’t have to.

I once sought perfection, thinking I could overcome anything with enough hard work and kindness. I let other people hold me up on a pedestal, expecting perfection from me as well. I became used to being shamed, abused, and mistreated while someone else called it “accountability.” But when expectations are unreal, accountability doesn’t work.

Working mindfully is different than working hard. Perfection is an illusion. And kindness is always key. This, I now understand.

At 36, every space, person, career path, and so on, reminds me of something from the past. But now is now, and reminders are just that. Something to choose how you react to, as old self, or as the you that you are, now.

Hi. I used to own a retail store, a really big one. A huge storefront on 1st Ave in downtown Seattle, just 4 blocks from Pike Place Market. Long before that, I did fashion blogging. When the pandemic hit, I retreated into the world of sweatshirts and sweatpants and crying alone for months on end. Fashion didn’t matter. Or maybe, I just forgot the personal joy it could bring me when feeling so alone.

I started fashion blogging in 2010 as a way to find creative community alongside pursuing a career in graphic design, illustration and music. I was living a hyper isolated life. I was hand making jewelry and selling it via Etsy and pop up shops, and I’d often find myself choosing between socializing and furthering my business, the one thing financially sustaining me.  I’d think about how $2.50 worth of jewelry supplies could make me back at least double that, buying the $2.50 coffee from the coffee shop down the street felt like a waste of money. But then I’d find myself crying about how isolated I felt, alone in my home shared with a roommate who slept in the day and worked at night.

After years of building a business, in 2017, I found myself investing almost half a million dollars into a retail store with no loans. I never took that money for myself, the most I ever paid myself while managing a staff of 15 people was a 60k salary, nothing outrageous and far below the average of a CEO salary. I was still in a “sacrifice everything for your career” mindset. It was a fashion business, but the joy had been beat out of it for me. I was in an eternal cycle of survival mode, rarely prioritizing joy. I built a beautiful box of a store that trapped me in cycles of shame and unworthiness. Dressing up wasn’t fun. I was around people finally, but isolated still thinking as a boss, it’s inappropriate to be close with your staff.

In 2020, I shut it all down. I broke down and rebuilt myself. I’m still alone most of the time, but relearning, spending money on a coffee is an investment in me, not a waste. Dressing up to go to a coffee shop gives me immense joy. Being one of many tapping away on a computer at a coffee shop taking breaks to chat with people is exactly what I need.

I’ve missed painting as much as I’ve missed singing. Singing and painting embodied my identity as a teenager and college student (all the while not knowing that I was an Autistic kid, struggling hard to stay alive and surviving by self soothing through artistic expression.) And then I hit the ground running after college, seeking to turn my creativity into financial sustenance to survive capitalism. Boo. It sucked the joy out of so much I once felt so free and safe exploring. 

So, the other day, I thrifted this piece of art that was just a digital print, probably sold in a big box store, with the intention of using it as an affordable canvas, already framed.

Tonight I started listening to “Caste” by @isabelwilkerson while I painted and I remembered, it’s so much easier for my Autistic/ADHD brain to absorb verbal or text based information IF my hands are busy doing something that soothes me and I’m tapping into subconscious creative flow. This is how I learn, this is how I grow, this is how I translate information into art while also relaxing and self soothing.

Paint with me. And let me know how watching me paint makes you feel. I hope it soothes you as much as it soothes me to create.

Gave our basement bathroom a little makeover, cleansing, rebirth if you will. And I’ve been contemplating the same for myself. Spring cleaning in the literal and metaphorical senses resonates beautifully with where my mind is at right now. 

Contemplate this:
Art you once hung in your old apartment/house, objects of necessity you acquired at your old place, they’re not literally in the exact same spot at your new place, right? Sure, you use many of those objects in similar ways, some maybe exactly as you once did elsewhere, but art is hung in different places, some maybe couldn’t find a home in your new spot, and things are familiar but different.

The same goes for the self in any new situation you are in. Be it a new relationship, a new physical space, a new experience that reminds you of a previous one: yes, there are reminders amidst it all, there is some sameness, but there’s plenty of newness and subtle differences that push your growth and learning.

In rebirth of the self, scrapping the entirety of who you were to become someone completely different is shortsighted. Past you gained so much knowledge that can be applied to the new you! But some things must die, some must end, and that process is exactly that, a process. In new spaces we might project images of the old, blocking ourselves from seeing what’s truly there to be appreciated and prioritized. Same goes for relationships and even how you view yourself!

To create something beautiful, it’s not just about deleting or adding, it’s also about adapting and transformation. And I want that for myself, to savor the need to add, delete, adapt and transform amidst acceptance of present truths. I’m not interested in purging, I want to flow. This is the Spring Cleaning that is healing.

Getting back into business, baby.

There are things I love about running a small business and plenty I dislike. I’ve been in the small biz game since 2009. I opened my first Etsy shop immediately after graduating college with a degree in Studio Art. I’ve designed jewelry, home decor, done web design, illustration, portraiture and graphic design, I’ve built out websites, built a following of 1 million followers on Pinterest, spoke at numerous conferences, built out two storefronts, was featured on Oprah.com and Goop and tons of other websites, I’ve designed clothing, paper goods, written 6 guided journals, a home decor book and Im coming out with a tarot deck and book next year… I’ve been busy my whole life, going hard and for the majority of it, running on low fuel and high anxiety, driven by fear, trauma and scarcity.

I paused in so many ways in the middle of 2020. I stopped for the first time, slowed down, gave myself permission to say no, end major career paths that were hurting me more than doing good. And it wasn’t until 2022 that I finally felt like I could start living, slowly after about 2 years of mourning and grief triggered by so many needed endings.

And now it’s 2023. I’m a different person, profoundly more aware of what is good for me and what hurts. I’ve tested many things, gave my all in many ways and rejected a whole lot that ended up being wrong for me.

Now, I begin to rebuild. Im focusing on the things that fuel me on a deeper level. Im making art again. Im writing books still that fill my soul. Im running a podcast that gives me the opportunity to chat with incredible people, promote their work and hopefully inspire all who listen. Im working on rebuilding my website so I can sell goods that I love again, this time, in a much more sustainable way than I attempted in the past.

There are facet of old me still here, but the whole feels new. I am building, and I’m grateful to anyone who has tagged along with me from my many past selves to now.

Thanks for being here, watching me stretch, morph and grow. And I hope I can provide for you in meaningful ways now that I understand how best to provide for me.

How do you manage chores?

Every month, I create a chore chart like this.
Here are my methods for managing chores while also giving yourself the space to flow with your moods and changing energy levels.

• 1 main daily task
• 7 weekly tasks 
• Each week, place each task on a different day than the week before to add variety so you don’t get bored
• Name the week that you are on your moon cycle (aka, dealing with your period if you have a uterus) your Winter week. It’s the week you’re going to be most sluggish and need the most rest.
• Next is Spring: Prioritze added tasks that bring newness to your space like a deep clean, repainting a chair, repotting plants, etc.
• Summer: Plan tasks this week that you can rally friends to help with so it’s an social opportunity, plan your most creative household tasks.
• Autumn: Plan tasks that feel like nesting. Knock off any tasks you’ve been avoiding so that your week of winter can feel totally chill and calming. 

Have you ever considered planning your month around how your energy waxes and wanes depending on your moon cycle? Altering my expectations week to week based on my morphing energy levels has seriously changed my life and made for an overall happier mood. Sometimes it’s not about trying to become more consistent day to day but accepting that we are ever shifting creatures who flow like the seasons. Viewing my energy as something that is seasonal has actually created more consistency in my mood. My expectations are adaptable and that brings so much peace.

I’d love to hear what you think about shifting your monthly routines to support your seasons of self!

Well, my challenge from my therapist for the next two weeks is to do things that make me feel connected to my body. 

Taking photos of what I am wearing is a helper when I’m unconsciously avoiding the fact that I am a human with a body. When I’m experiencing sensory overload, especially when I’m feeling like my clothes are too tight or my boobs are too big, I just want to disassociate. Now that I understand I am Autistic, a diagnosis I finally received at age 34 (I’m 36 now), I understand why I have a visceral response to sensations that feel uncomfortable. I used to be called dramatic by people who thought I was overreacting to discomfort. And Autism explains it. When I feel emotional discomfort, I experience physical discomfort. When I experience a new physical sensation, or tightness, swelling, etc it almost creates a panic within me. I used to avoid being touched by people. I wouldn’t hug people until my mid 20s. Sensory things just a a lot for me.

Fashion was a huge helper for me as a teenager and 20 something as a way to direct attention away from my body and on to an artistic practice. Exploring fashion helped me enjoy being in my body. And I accidentally created a career out of it with “influencer” work and building a retail business. I don’t do either work now, and I can see I’m more detached from my body because of it. Right now all I can feel are the ulcers in my mouth from allergies scratching against my braces. Ugh.

So I’m getting back on the “take photos of my outfit” train because I need it for my mental health. I need to see and feel and connect with my body for the benefit of my heart and mind, my relationships, and so much more.

Here’s what I’m wearing today. It’s comforting. And stylish enough. 

Ps, I’m designing some stylish comfort focused clothing for you and me. This pandemic has taught me that comfort is a priority, but style is important too in self expression.

Would love to hear your thoughts on style, comfort, feeling connected/disconnected from your body, sensory issues, etc. Being human is weird!

The question creatives always get asked is “where do you get inspiration?” Wanna know my answer?

1. I check in with my feelings and ask myself: how can you convey your mood or challenge it by creating art today?

2. I check in with my body and ask: What is most prominently standing out to you senses? Is there a texture that is soothing or irritating you? Can that be conveyed in a piece of art today?

3. I check in with my ego: What is something you are avoidant of? Is there a color you are not often drawn to, and can you find a way to integrate it into your art today?

So, what were my answers that lead to creating this piece?
• I feel like I’m buzzing and irritable because allergies.
• My body feels overwhelmed by the conflicting joy of Spring sunshine and the way that allergies set off a lot of my auto immune disorders, depression, anxiety and ADHD.
• I rarely use yellow in my work.

And what did these answers lead to…

The first piece in a series of paintings inspired by POLLEN!

Pollen.
You do wonders for bugs and bees and help to make nature so gorgeous, but damn you mess up my sinuses, my gut, my immune system and my mental health. It’s a lot hate relationship that you and I have.

I’d like to thank Zyrtec and Flonase for helping me lower my negative feels towards pollen, but even more so, thanks to paint for helping me transform and irritant into something that brings me so much joy.

I almost always want to paint, expect when chronic illnesses flare and my brain and body say, “it’s a no.”

I deal with autoimmune disorders that cause major inflammation, from swollen joints to swollen skin to swelling in the brain that causes depression and anxiety. I’m also on the Autism spectrum. Autistic people often have the weird magical thing where when we feel emotional pain, we also feel it physically. It all means that I need a lot more rest than the average person, I need low sensory spaces and experiences. And it’s no wonder the many careers I’ve held in life have all revolves around self-soothing and facilitating soothing for others.

Painting is a source of soothing, emotionally and physically. When my fingers feel as swollen as they do right now, it’s a no. But when my fingers feel ok to paint, zoning in on painting helps me direct attention away from body pain and into a meditative state of mind. 

Do you have any practices that get you into that beautiful and much needed meditative stage? I can almost always rely on painting, tarot and and YA novels to get my mind off of emotional and physical pain. 

But when pain is at a 10/10, all I can do is rest. And crack jokes :)

It means so much to me to feel supported by literally anyone on this ding dong app, in my pursuit of creating art again. From old life long pals to new people who land here because of a random reel, Im grateful for you. I’ve got a new batch of pieces that will go live on my website on Wednesday at noon (April 19) and I hope one of these beauties resonates with you!

This is an evolving process. I graduated with a degree in Studio Art in 2009, and just now, in 2023, am I’m pursuing building a career in fine art. It’s not a rush, I’m taking my time to play and experiment, not fully commit to any one style yet. Sure, some series that are cohesive feels right to release in batches. But with each completed batch, I feel an urge to try something new. So within this one, you’ll see a few pieces that sort of stand on their own and some that flow clearly with others. Some are first steps into new territories. Decisions made that gave me opportunity to explore ideas and try on new creative suits to feel what feels right. By you purchasing one of my pieces, I hope you feel like you are joining me on this journey, in my growth as an artist and person, I hope you use my art as marking points of your own growth. “Who were you, where were you at mentally when you purchased this art? And why did is resonate with you?” I hope you reflect on those questions when you’ve still got a piece of mine in your home in 10 years while also seeing my art evolve over that time.

Making art, “being” an artist is an evolution. To stay stagnant is a nightmare. Security is nice, but I’m made to take risks, to keep trying, to keep morphing, testing and exploring. As i get older, I crave security more and more, but the itch to keep changing doesn’t go away. I need to make.
Art has always been that space for me where the exploration of the unknown, the following of intuition and trust in self expression, flourish. Though I’ve had major career success in various fields in my past, never did I feel like my inner self was flourishing within the shiny boxes I placed myself in.
But art, especially fine art, this is where I want to be. Thanks for supporting me in my truest dream come true.

My latest paintings are now available at ShopMooreaSeal.com! Could your kid do them? Sure, if they’re willing to work on the same thing for 5-15 hours. I would take ZERO offense if a little kid or even a grown up copied my art. For me, this is a therapeutic experience. I live with ADHD, Autism, C-PTSD, and plenty of other things that are invisible that make existing kinda hard. I dealt with these things in silence as a kid and wasn’t diagnosed until I was in my 30s. Art was a helper and healer back then and it still is today. 

If you purchase one of these pieces, I hope you see and feel a source of healing and comfort within them. I hope you feel my heart and mind and soul within them. I hope you find relief when you look at them. And I hope you encourage any kids in your life to make art and whatever level, because art heals.

Thank you for supporting me and my work. It means a lot.

A loose paint sesh. I vacillate between wanting to get really detailed and structured within my paintings and wanting to flow freely and loose. Maybe it’s my Gemini spirit, I need the polarity, the contrasts, the dance between the two. 

Different styles of painting require different parts of my body to engage. With soft and loose abstracted art, the movement flows from my shoulders and wrists, swishing and swaying to create curves of varying sizes, a bouncy sort of play in flat space.

When I’m painting my grids of color pieces, it’s all about my elbow directing when to start and stop. My wrist stays still and strong, my fingers become solid points that back up all the structure that holds my body together between my elbows and finger tips. The movement of my body dictates how and what I paint, and my mood and emotions determine the colors. 

It’s beautiful to realize, my painting style is a somatic practice, a sort of self soothing, a healing, an art of nurturing and caring for the self, listening, trusting my intuition, being in tune with my inner and outer self. 

I hope that when you watch me paint or when you look at my paintings, you feel soothed. 

I currently taking a course on Visual Thinking Strategies. It’s a method of facilitation that prioritizes student-driven learning and the creation of community. In traditional art education, there’s an emphasis placed on memorization of a pieces name, artist, date, and whatever the artist says the piece is about. In VTS, education is led by students sharing what they see in a piece, affirming all views are true and valid, and in doing so, students gain actual aesthetic development; critical thinking skills, social and emotional development, agency, language development and community. 

In taking this course, I hope that I can facilitate art education with kids and adults in the future through a therapeutic lens. I think the art I create has the potential to offer personal growth opportunities for the viewers if they look in a way that validates their own experiences, perspectives and opinions. 

So, all that being said, I encourage you to look at what I’m painting and how I am painting, and share what you see!

Past work to remind you that just because an artist chooses abstraction, it doesn’t mean they don’t have the capacity to do realism. Just because an artist might choose to paint a landscape or patterns, it doesn’t mean they don’t know how to paint the human form. 

I LOVE portraiture. In the early 2010s, I used to illustrate portraits for bloggers. But after so many women asked me to alter their face or body, I stopped. I have always sought to promote body positivity through my portraits and being asked to be a artistic plastic surgeon really made me uncomfortable down to my core.

Maybe I’ll get back into offering portraits in the future. But I’ll need to have some solid things set in writing around body positivity, self acceptance and how profoundly I believe all bodies are beautiful. 

For now, sticking with patterns and abstractions feels safe and soothing for all, less triggering and challenging emotionally. And I want to assist in soothing 💛

I want to get in the habit of sharing my daily painting. This summer, I made the commitment to myself to get back into painting after years away. After being diagnosed as Autistic at age 33, my connection to the arts gained a far deeper meaning. I have always felt more grounded, more secure in myself, like I can communicate better, regulate my emotions, and self sooth if I am making art daily. 
I wanted to be an artist as a kid. I loved any type of art I could access and explore. I survived high school thanks to becoming heavily involved in choir, singing in 3 choirs, a quartet and starting a semi-professional choir outside of school with a few friends in and out of high school. I was singing 40+ hours a week as a teenager which I know profoundly supported my well-being while struggling in so many ways.
I barely made it through college. But once I finally let myself pursue studio art and visual narrative after years of trying to conform to tracks that other people told me were more practical, I thrived. I never did well in classes that required memorization, and I struggled with comprehension. But I could communicate through visual art and song writing.

When I graduated college in 2009, the recession again made me believe I could not be an artist and had to pursue more “practical” work. I ended up achieving a lot, but down paths that depleted me rather than fueled me.

2020 was a painful blessing, an opportunity to STOP. To learn who I am and what I need. I got divorced. Closed my retail store. And gained awareness of my who I am at my core by embracing queerness and Autism as my truths.

And in 2023, this summer, I finally told myself: and you are an artist. So paint. And I have been almost every day. No matter what I am feeling, painting is an answer. It’s a safe space. It’s a communication tool. It’s freeing and comforting and empowering. It’s transformative. I love written words, but I love visual art even more. 

I hope by sharing my story, that you too give yourself permission to be whatever you want to be, to do what you want to do, to embrace who you are, and love what and who you love.

You are worth your time. Pursue you.

#ArtHack Canvases are so expensive! Sometimes, just to cost of supplies alone stops people from getting into art and finding an outlet that fuels their soul. Here’s a tip for finding affordable canvases for your art adventures!

• Check out the art section at your local thrift shop. There will likely be both framed and unframed art you have full permission to paint over.
• Ross, Marshall’s and other discount stores often sell stock art that was produced by a corporation and made in mass quantities to be sold at low prices. Don’t feel guilty about painting over this stuff, it’s a cheap way to find uniquely shapes canvases already framed and ready for you to reuse and upcycle!

A new canvas from an art store that’s 36 x 36 inches can cost around $100. The same size art, framed and found at a thrift store or discount store is typically 3-4 times cheaper! What a deal!

Go reduce, reuse and recycle art that has been discarded or overproduced and transform it into something meaningful. You deserve access to modes of self expression without enormous financial burden.

I’ve sold 1.4 million copies of my books, sold thousands of pieces of my jewelry line, I’ve rebuilt a career in fine art painting after years away and developed my own print line, I’ve written 6 guided journals, one home decor book, a line of planners, note books, desktop products and more and I’m currently designing a tarot deck and an accompanying workbook to support your mental health, I’ve stocked my work in over 500 stores world wide, I owned a retail store for 7 years and built out a 6,000 sq ft store and offices, and I am nowhere near done exploring a multi-passionate life and multi-hyphenated career.

How to begin:

• Use what you have: I started with $10, a pair of jewelry pliers and some thrifted jewelry that I turned into something new and sold on Etsy.com in 2009. Price low and let it grow.

• You can’t expect immediate success: Look, creative careers are time consuming! Put in the time now and you’ll see it pay off in the future. The struggle right now is worth future success.

• Find your people: The most important thing in building any creative career is building community! Cooperation over competition. The more you uplift other creatives, the more support you’ll get too! Reach out to creatives you admire, ask questions, show your support and look for ways to connect and collaborate. 

• Be willing to fail, multiple times over: it’s my WILLINGNESS to fail that keeps me going. I believe in failing forwards. Every thing you make is an experiment that builds upon what you’ve already tried. Enjoy the experimentation process! Share your journey! And know, your success will come if you are willing to fail.

• Just do it: seriously, just start! I know, sometimes starting is the hardest part. But this is your one life, you don’t know how much time you have to explore, experiment and create. So just do it! You wanna write a book? Start a substack, give yourself weekly writing goals, and go! You want to be an artist? Take an hour each morning to draw, paint, study other artists, commit to being bad until you get better. No one starts out great, we all have the privilege of getting to grow. So start now!

The patriarchal King/Queen/Knight/Page just doesn’t speak to our queer and autistic spirits and we think you don’t need it either. We reframe the progression of the court cards with new names:

Apprentice (Page): an eager student in the journey of gaining wisdom.
Champion (Knight): early triumph and victories won, but grounding and inner wisdom still needed.
Oracle (Queen): deep inner awareness and knowing are harnessed, but still further to go for universal comprehension of wisdom.
Elder (king): wisdom gained from every aspect of living and existing, inner and outer awareness, a harmony of complex knowledge.

Do you see how no gendering is needed to achieve the growth seen through the court cards of the tarot? Anyone of any gender or no gender at all deserves to feel and see their own growth through exploring the journey of tarot.

Let me show you the prep work that goes into mapping out a painting. I’m exploring quilt patterns for an upcoming show in January with @brandonjwashington and @annah.kim.art at @slip_belltown in Seattle. 

I’m painting a traditional American quilt to represent the quietly oppressive yet pretty presenting society of America. I moved here in 1994 from a village of 400 people in rural England and was overwhelmed by American perfectionism. I didn’t understand America’s glorification of “pioneers” and settlers”, though I did understand that England also was the major originator of oppression in the US. 

I moved to a “pioneer” town when I was 8 in rural Northern California and I remember all of the girls my age being obsessed with the Little House on the Prairie books and their moms were quilters and Evangelical Christians, a brand of Christianity I didn’t know about until I moved here. I read the box car kids and thought, why does America glorify a book about orphans on the run, evading police and having to escape foster care splitting them up… all to be rescued by a rich grandfather. American patriarchy saves the day… Why are we not talking about the f*cked up foster care system globally? Why are kids into playing “cowboys and Indians” and yet we’re not learning about Native Americans in a white washed country?

All of this to say, it took me a long time to realize and accept, I am American. My parents were ex-pats in England. I thought I was British. I was weird to American kids for what I thought was being raised in a different culture. But there was more I didn’t understand that made me weird.

I am queer and autistic, and I learned to mask and hide inklings of my queerness and undiagnosed autism when I moved to the US. And now that I am out and unmasked, I think of the pretty mask I put on to adapt to and survive American culture as a traditional quilt that suffocates and holds down whatever is wrapped up in it. 

Planning this painting has been SO uncomfortable. It’s felt icky and triggering and yuck, which feels strange for such a simple and pretty image of a quilt. But that’s what it is. A 😷 mask I took on, and one now off.
